Here Horace abruptly elevates the astute- ness of Mercury from the playful thefts of infancy to the wise caution , with which he leads the innocent and helpless through the severest dangers; and then naturally, and with all his inimitable terseness, the poet represents him as condueting no less safely the souls of the dead. Throughout all those stanzas, from the theft of oxen, when Mercury was an infant in his cradle, to his crowning mission as the conductor of souls departed, the same ruling idea of stealtlz is preserved and dei- fied. Mercury steals the kine from Apollo, he steals Priam through the Grecian camp, he steals souls through the passage between earth and Hades‚-—all with a union of guarded secrecy and imperturbable serenity which, throughout the more playful attributes of Hermes, imply the gran- deur and inspire the awe that characterise a supernatura] being. No deity can be more exclusively Greek in this* combination of open joy- ousness and mystic power. It was a type of divinity as impossible to be conceived by the Latins as by the Germanic and Scandinavian races, though they all worshipped a Mercurius.
